<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-perf-improve" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Improving Performance</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Once you've used profiling to identify a bottleneck, you need to make
        it faster. It's difficult to provide general advice on improving
        performance, but I try to distil some of the most important techniques
        into this chapter. I'll illustrate each technique with a small example
        that helps understand the idea, but don't forget to also apply them to
        your actual problem.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-perf-improve-intro">
      <title>Code organisation</title>

      <p>
        There are two traps that are easy to fall into when trying to make your
        code faster:
      </p>

      <p><ol>
        <li><p>
          Writing faster but incorrect code.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          Writing code that you think is faster, but is actually no faster
          (or even slower).
        </p></li>
      </ol></p>

      <p>
        The target of your optimisation efforts should always be the bottleneck
        you found through profiling, and you should always use microbenchmarking
        to verify that your change made a real difference.
      </p>
    </section>

  </chapter>
